  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">RadioLAB: Community-based radio training and support for advocacy and awareness raising</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Radialistas Apasionadas y Apasionados (until 31/12/2016: Fundacion Radialistas Apasionadas y Apasionados) was created in 2001 to contribute to the democratisation of communications, especially of  radio, with particular focus on gender, citizenship and protection of the environment. It was set up as a production and training centre for radio broadcasters from all continents, although prioritising Latin America and the Caribbean. During these 15 years, Radialistas have been constantly expanding their services. Their Radioteca.net, a social network of radios, is the largest portal in Latin America for exchanging audios among community radios.

This new, three-year project is aimed at further innovation in Radialistas&#x2019; work. They believe that, currently, their goal should no longer be to increase the number of audios, courses or manuals, but to modernise, invent, rethink, and engage more people in the task of understanding how to work in this new, digital era. Hence, this project proposes to create the &#x201C;RadioLAB&#x201D;: a collaborative laboratory of radio experimentation. A space/network of experienced producers that would allow them to rethink community radio in the digital era, and look for new production formats, unique forms of interaction and methodologies for radio training.

At the end of this project Radialistas hope that at least 200 community radios in Latin America will be working with new radio formats and approaches, using Internet and digital technologies. They hope to achieve this through a network of 6 to 10 active organisations, media and/or production centres. 

Radialistas also hope that community radio stations in Latin America will recognise the political importance of using open source software as a precondition for democratising communications in the digital era. To achieve this objective, they will be producing articles, manuals and video tutorials, and supporting the Network for Community Radios and Free Software.</narrative>
  </description>
